# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1940-detroit-tigers-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1894-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1894 throughout the world.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] The **1900 Detroit Tigers season** was the Tigers' first in the American League, which received recognition as a major league one year later in 1901.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers finished in fourth place out of eight teams with a record of 71–67, 12+1⁄2 games behind Charles Comiskey's Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Detroit's home games were played at Bennett Park.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Outfielder Dick Harley led the team with a .325 batting average, 77 runs scored, and 47 stolen bases.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Sport McAllister led in slugging percentage (.383), and Frank Dillon led in extra-base hits (30).
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Roscoe Miller led the team with a 19–9 win-loss record for a .679 win percentage.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Jack Cronin led in innings pitched (372) and strikeouts (121).
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Burns and George Stallings had spent large sums of money for "releases of star players" and had paid "major league salaries" to the majority of the players.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1901 Chicago White Stockings season** was their first season as a major league team, and their second season in Chicago.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] It was also the inaugural season of American League as a major league.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings had a very balanced lineup, which was led by outfielders Dummy Hoy and Fielder Jones, and scored the most runs in the AL.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] They relied primarily on speed, as Frank Isbell, Sam Mertes, and Jones finished 1–2–3 in stolen bases.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The pitching staff was anchored by Clark Griffith, who went 24–7 with a 2.67 ERA.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The **1901 Detroit Tigers season** was the Tigers' 2nd season in Major League Baseball.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The team was a charter member of the American League, which was originally formed as the minor-league Western League, of which it had also been a charter member.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers finished in third place with a record or 74–61, 8+1⁄2 games behind the Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Most of Detroit's home games were played at Bennett Park, with Sunday games played at Burns Park due to Detroit's blue laws.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Roscoe Miller (23–13) led the team in wins and was the Tigers' first 20-game winner.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] His performance headlined a strong pitching staff that had the third lowest ERA (3.30) in the American League.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Joe Yeager had an ERA of 2.61, for the second best Adjusted ERA+ in the AL, behind Cy Young.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The offense was not as strong however, scoring 741 runs – fifth among the eight teams in the league.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The team's best hitters were shortstop Kid Elberfeld (.308 average) and center fielder Jimmy Barrett (.293 average; 110 runs).
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers had played their games at Bennett Park since 1896, but the graduation to a major league meant that there would now be games scheduled on Sundays, which was forbidden by Detroit's blue laws.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] In order to avoid running afoul of this stricture, owner James D.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Burns built a ballpark on his own property in Springwells Township, Michigan just outside the Detroit city limits.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Named Burns Park, the Tigers would play their Sunday home games there for the 1901 and 1902 seasons.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] During the 1901 season, Detroit attracted 259,430 fans at home and 238,100 on the road, for a total of 447,428.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Detroit ranked third behind Chicago and Boston in overall attendance.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] 1902 was the second year for the **Detroit Tigers** in the newly formed American League.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] The team finished in seventh place with a record of 58–77 (.385), 30½ games behind the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] The 1902 Tigers were outscored by their opponents 657 runs to 566.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] The team's attendance at Bennett Park was 189,469, sixth out of the eight teams in the AL.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] Detroit's blue laws prevented the Tigers from playing baseball at Bennett Park on Sundays.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] As a result, the Tigers played their Sunday home games for the season at Burns Park; a stadium constructed by owner James D.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] The **1902 Philadelphia Athletics season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] The team finished first in the American League with a record of 83 wins and 53 losses.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] In 1902, the Philadelphia Phillies obtained an injunction, effective only in Pennsylvania, barring Athletics' second baseman Nap Lajoie from playing baseball for any team other than the Phillies.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] Lajoie had played for the Athletics in 1901, and appeared in just one game in 1902 before the injunction went into effect.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] The American League responded by transferring Lajoie's contract to the Cleveland Bronchos, who were subsequently known as the "Naps" in Lajoie's honor for several seasons.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] Following the A's pennant winning season, the *Philadelphia Inquirer* organized a championship parade for the team through the city on Monday night, September 30, 1902.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] The team proceeded in open carriages and were reviewed by Philadelphia Mayor Ashbridge in front of the *Inquirer'*s building on Market Street.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] "There were more than 25,000 base ball enthusiasts from Philadelphia and nearly every town within a radius of twenty miles of the city in the parade.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] A thousand effigies of the "white elephant" were carried by the paraders.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] There were fifteen bands and twenty fife and drum corps in line to furnish music for the marchers." It was estimated that more than 200,000 turned out for the parade.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The **1903 Boston Americans season** was the third season for the professional baseball franchise that later became known as the Boston Red Sox.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Americans finished first in the American League (AL) with a record of 91 wins and 47 losses, 14+1⁄2 games ahead of the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Boston went on to participate in the first World Series held between the AL and National League (NL) champions.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Americans won the 1903 World Series in eight games over the Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team was managed by Jimmy Collins and played its home games at Huntington Avenue Grounds.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Prior to the regular season, the team held spring training in Macon, Georgia.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Cy Young was a coach for the Mercer University baseball team, also based in Macon.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Boston Americans played an exhibition game against Mercer University (with Cy Young pitching for Mercer) on March 23; the outcome being a 13─2 victory for Boston.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team's longest losing streak was three games, which occurred twice; April 20–23 and September 22–23.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team's longest game was 12 innings, which occurred three times.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The offense was led by Buck Freeman, who hit 13 home runs and had 104 RBIs, and Patsy Dougherty with a .331 batting average.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] It was Freeman's third consecutive season with at least 100 RBIs.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The pitching staff was led by Cy Young, who made 40 appearances (35 starts) and pitched 34 complete games with a 28–9 record and 2.08 ERA, while striking out 176 in 341+2⁄3 innings.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team had two other 20-game winners; Bill Dinneen (21–13) and Tom Hughes (20–7).
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team had three games end in a tie; July 31 at Washington, August 29 at Washington, and September 25 vs.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Tie games are not counted in league standings, but player statistics during tie games are counted.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Boston had an 11-game winning streak from May 28 through June 8, to put themselves in the AL lead.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] While they briefly fell into second place in mid-June, behind Philadelphia, Boston then won 9-of-10 to recapture the lead, which they held through the end of the season.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Americans met the Pittsburgh Pirates in the first modern World Series, an agreement between the AL and the NL as a post-season tournament.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The "Amerks" won the best-of-nine series in eight games; after falling behind, 3–1, they won four games in a row, clinching the championship at their home field, the Huntington Avenue Grounds, in Boston.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] The **1940 Detroit Tigers season** was their 40th since they entered the American League in 1901.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] The team won the American League pennant with a record of 90–64, finishing just one game ahead of the Cleveland Indians and just two games ahead of the New York Yankees.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] It was the sixth American League pennant for the Tigers.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] The team went on to lose the 1940 World Series to the Cincinnati Reds 4 games to 3.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] The 1940 Tigers won the American League pennant with a record of 90–64.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] They narrowly beat the Cleveland Indians led by Bob Feller in a tight pennant race that went back-and-forth right down to the end of the season.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers outscored their opponents 888 to 717 for the season.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] Catcher **Birdie Tebbetts** played for the Tigers from 1936 to 1947, missing the 1943–1945 seasons for military service.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] He was chosen four times for the AL All Star team.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] In 1940, Tebbetts hit .296 and led all AL catchers in assists (89), errors (17) and double plays (10).
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] Catching duties were shared with **Billy Sullivan, Jr.**.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] He hit .309 with a .399 on-base percentage and .450 slugging percentage for the 1940 Tigers.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] Sullivan played in 5 of 7 games of the 1940 World Series for the Tigers, scoring three runs with a .389 on-base percentage.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] His father, Billy Sullivan, was also a catcher for the Tigers in 1916.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] First baseman **Rudy York** started as a catcher in 1937.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] In 1940, the Tigers persuaded Hank Greenberg to move to left field, allowing York to take over at first base.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] The experiment was successful, as York finished 2nd in the AL in RBIs (134), total bases (343), and extra base hits (85).
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] He also finished 8th in the AL MVP voting, 3rd in the major leagues in times on base (279) and doubles (46) and 4th in the AL in slugging percentage (.583).
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] York was among the American League leaders in home runs for 11 consecutive seasons from 1937 to 1947, and his .503 slugging percentage as a Tiger ranks #4 in franchise history.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] Shortstop **Dick Bartell** was known as one of the most ferocious competitors of his era.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] In 1940, he hit only .233 for the Tigers, but he had 76 walks boosting his on-base percentage by 100 points to .335.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] He scored 76 runs and drove in 53 runs for the 1940 season.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] Bartell finished 12th in the AL MVP voting in 1940.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] Third baseman **Pinky Higgins** was the team's starting third baseman from 1939 to 1944.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] In 1940, he hit .271, drove in 76 runs, hit 13 home runs, and walked 61 times, boosting his on-base percentage to .357.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] Left fielder "Hammerin' Hank" Greenberg was the team's and the league's MVP.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] He was awarded the AL Most Valuable Player award for the second time in his career, the first person to win the MVP award at two different positions (1935 at first base, 1940 at left field).
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] In 1940, Greenberg led the major leagues in RBIs (150), extra base hits (99), slugging percentage (.670), OPS (1.103), total bases (384), doubles (50), and runs created (166).
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] He also led the AL in home runs (41) and at bats per home run (14.0).
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] He was 4th in AL in batting average (.340) and 2nd in the major leagues in on-base percentage (.433), runs scored (134), and times on base (289).
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] Greenberg was drafted into the military in early 1941 (one of the first major league players to be drafted) and lost parts of five seasons (1941–1945) to military service.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] Center fielder **Barney McCosky** also had a tremendous year.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] For the 1940 season, McCosky led the major leagues in hits (200) and triples (19).
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] He was also 3rd in the major leagues in runs scored (123), and 4th in the AL in times on base (268), 5th in the AL in batting (.340).
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] In the World Series, he hit .304 (7-for-23) with five runs.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] McCosky finished 16th in the 1940 AL MVP voting.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] Since 1940, the only Tiger to exceed McCosky's 19 triples is Curtis Granderson in 2007.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] Right fielder **Pete Fox** played 82 games in right field, hitting .289 with a .403 slugging percentage.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] Hall of Famer Earl Averill was acquired by the Tigers in 1938 and was a backup outfielder for the 1940 team.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] Closer **Al Benton** led the major leagues in saves (17) and was second in the major leagues in games finished (35).
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] Rookie **Floyd Giebell** was one of the most interesting stories of the 1940 season.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] Giebell made his major league debut in September 1940 as a 30-year-old rookie.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] Giebel pitched a pair of complete game victories and gave up only two runs in 18 innings for an earned run average of 1.00.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] On September 27, 1940, the Tigers needed one more win to clinch the pennant.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] With Bob Feller scheduled to pitch for the Indians, Detroit manager Del Baker decided to start Giebell rather than "waste" his aces Bobo Newsom or Schoolboy Rowe.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] *Time* magazine described Giebell at the time as "a gawky stringbean" — Geiebell was 6 ft 2+1⁄2 in (189 cm) and 172 pounds (78 kg) —who "looked like a sacrificial lamb as he ambled out to the mound." But, as *Time* reported after the game, Giebell was "no lamb" that day.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] Instead, "[w]ith cunning change of pace and the control of an oldtimer, the green-as-grass rookie shut out the Indians 2-to-0." Feller gave up only 3 hits for the day, but one of them was a 2-run wind-blown home run by Rudy York.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] Giebell shut out the Indians for 9 innings in one of the great "David vs.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] The **1940 World Series** featured the Detroit Tigers and the Cincinnati Reds, with the Tigers losing in 7 games.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] In Game 1, the Tigers beat the Reds, 7–2.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] It was the 10th straight World Series loss for a National League team.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers scored five runs in the 2nd inning, and Bruce Campbell added a two-run home run.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] Bobo Newsom held the Reds to eight hits.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] Newsom's father, visiting from South Carolina, died in a Cincinnati hotel room the day after watching his son win Game 1.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] In Game 2, Bucky Walters gave the NL its first World Series game victory, 5–3, since Carl Hubbell beat the Yankees in 1937.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] Jimmy Ripple hit a two-run home run in the 3rd inning, and Walters gave up only 3 hits.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] In Game 3, the Tigers won, 7–3, before a crowd of almost 53,000 at Briggs Stadium.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers had 9 hits and 19 total bases in the 7th and 8th innings off the Reds.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] Paul Derringer‚ who had lost 4 World Series starts going back to 1931‚ finally got a win.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] Detroit starter Dizzy Trout did not make it out of the third inning.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] In Game 5, Bobo Newsom got the start for Detroit, just three days after his father's death.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] Bobo said he was going to pitch the game for his dad.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] In front of 55,000 fans in Detroit, he shut out the Reds, as the Tigers won 8–0, and took a 3–2 lead in the Series.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] In Game 6, Bucky Walters got the win for the Reds with a 4–0 shutout.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] The concluding game was a loss for the Tigers, as Bobo Newsom was called on to start on only one day's rest.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] Detroit got an unearned run in the 3rd inning to take a 1–0 lead.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] Newsom pitched well, allowing only two runs in the 7th inning.
[src:1940-detroit-tigers-season/1940-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers scored only once, and the Reds won, 2–1.
